## When to commit

- Commit when a unit of work is completed. Do not leave uncommitted changes at session end or when switching tasks.
- **Granularity**: One logical change per commit. Do not mix unrelated changes; do not split one logical change into many trivial commits. Keep commits reviewable and easy to revert.
- **Do not commit**: Auto-generated summary docs (e.g. REVIEW.md, SUMMARY.md, CHANGES.md). Prefer not creating them; if created, do not add to the repo — use README or existing docs instead.

## Workflow

**This workspace (`Cursor` dotfiles / rules) uses `main` only.** There is no `develop` branch; integration and releases both target `main`.

- **Always branch**: Create a feature/fix branch from up-to-date `main` before starting work. Do not commit directly to `main` (use a topic branch, then merge).
- **main**: single long-lived branch. Default on the remote. Merge `feature/`, `feat/`, `fix/`, `bugfix/`, `docs/` branches here after review or local verification.
- **feature/fix branches**: branch from **`main`**. Example flow: `git checkout main && git pull` → `git checkout -b feat/my-change` → work → merge (or PR) into `main`.
- **Releases**: Every push that updates a remote branch must include a new semantic version tag on the pushed tip commit (see **Push and version tags** below). Deploy target is defined per project.

**New repository**

1. Initial branch: `main` (`git branch -M main` if needed). First push: `git push -u origin main`.
2. Set the remote **default branch** to `main`.
3. Ongoing work: topic branches from `main`, merge back to `main`.

**Optional (recommended on GitHub/GitLab)**: Protect `main` (require PR/review, block force-push) if the host supports it.

## Push and version tags

**Rule:** Whenever you `git push` a branch to the remote, you **must** also create and push a **new** semantic version tag that points at the commit the remote branch will reference after the push (the tip you are publishing).

1. Determine the next `vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH` using **Versioning (SemVer)** below and the latest existing tag (`git tag -l 'v*' --sort=-v:refname | head -1`). If no tag exists yet, start at **`v0.1.0`** unless the project already documents a different initial version.
2. Create an **annotated** tag: `git tag -a vX.Y.Z -m "release vX.Y.Z"` (message may briefly describe the change set).
3. Push branch and tag together, e.g. `git push -u origin <branch>` then `git push origin vX.Y.Z`.

Do not push a branch update without pushing its matching version tag in the same release step. If a push is retried without new commits, do not create duplicate tags; only tag when the remote tip commit changes.

## Versioning (SemVer)

**Tag format:** `vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH` (leading `v`, e.g. `v1.2.3`). The numeric part follows [Semantic Versioning 2.0.0](https://semver.org/) semantics.

### MAJOR (`X`.y.z)

Increment when the change is **not backward compatible** for consumers of the repo or published artifacts.

- Removing or renaming public APIs, config keys, CLI flags, or documented behavior that users rely on
- Changing defaults in a way that breaks existing setups
- Dropping support for a platform or tool version that users still expect

**Examples:** remove a deprecated integration; rename a required settings file; change rule format so old files are invalid.

### MINOR (x.`Y`.z)

Increment when you add **backward-compatible** functionality or meaningful, compatible improvements.

- New features, scripts, MCP integrations, or optional configuration
- New documentation sections that describe new capability
- Deprecations **announced** but old behavior still works

**Examples:** add a new optional rule file; new `feat` commits that extend behavior without breaking old usage.

### PATCH (x.y.`Z`)

Increment for **backward-compatible** fixes and small maintenance that do not warrant a minor release.

- Bug fixes, security patches, typo corrections in docs when behavior is unchanged
- Internal refactors with no user-visible contract change
- **Routine pushes** on the same branch that only accumulate small compatible changes (default bump when unsure between patch and minor)

**Examples:** `fix` commits; `docs` typo; `chore` that does not add user-facing features.

### Choosing among MAJOR / MINOR / PATCH on a push

- If the push contains **any** breaking change → **MAJOR**
- Else if the push adds **user-visible or documented** new capability → **MINOR**
- Else → **PATCH**

Pre-release identifiers (e.g. `v1.2.3-rc.1`) are optional; use only if the team agrees; otherwise stay on `vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH` only.

## Naming

- **Branches**: `feature/xxx` or `feat/xxx`, `fix/xxx` or `bugfix/xxx`, `docs/xxx`
  - e.g. `feature/user-profile`, `fix/login-timeout`
- **Tags**: semantic version, e.g. `v1.0.0`
